    <text>
        <front>
            <div type="summary">
                <p>
                <persName>Barbara Gee</persName> writes to <persName>Leonard Woolf</persName>, in order to thank him for the 
                last five years, in which she worked for him. She also thanks him 
                for the &#xA3;25 he gave her as a bonus. She feels like she did not get 
                to say a proper goodbye, which is why she has chosen to write him to 
                express these feelings. 
                </p>
            </div>
        </front>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date when="1946-08-05">
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine> 
                            20. William Road
                            <lb/>    Hitchin
                            <lb/>    Heits 
                        </addrLine>
                    </address>
                    <salute>
                        Dear <persName key="Q703935"><choice><abbr>Mr.</abbr><expan>Mister</expan></choice> Woolf</persName>,
                    </salute>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <lb/>   Thank you very much 
                    <lb/>   indeed for your kind letters, and 
                    <lb/>   cheque for &#xA3;25 <note><p>According to the Bank of England, &#xA3;25 in 1946 would be the same as &#xA3;910.51 nowadays.</p></note> as bonus for the 
                    <lb/>   past year, it was nice of you 
                    <lb/>   to write to me and I do appreciate
                    <lb/>   it and, needless to say, the 
                    <lb/>   cheque will be most useful! 
                    <lb/>   I quite understand that 
                    <lb/>   in the general upheaval there was 
                    <lb/>   no opportunity of saying goodbye
                    <lb/>   and I would like to say how 
                    <lb/>   nice it was working for the 
                    <lb/>   press <note><p>Leonard Woolf and his wife Virginia Woolf, were the founders of the Hogarth Press. The press ran from 1917 until 1946, when the company got merged with another press.</p></note> for the five years I was 
                    <lb/>   with you. 
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                    <lb/> Yours sincerely, 
                    <lb/>    <persName key="MAPP0050">Barbara Gee</persName>. 
                    </salute>
                    <signed/>
                    <seg>
                    </seg>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
